    "body": "Compact block filter request might occur when the block has been already processed (and advertised), but the filter is not yet ready, this might lead to a disconnect by a peer who requested a filter.\r\n\r\nFixes: https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/issues/29655, https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/issues/27085 \r\nRelated discussion: [1](https://bnoc.xyz/t/request-block-filter-peers-being-disconnected-due-to-invalid-block-requests/101/2), [2](https://github.com/lightninglabs/neutrino/issues/338)\r\n\r\n**The problem:** \r\nBitcoin core receives a new block and processes it, then it advertises the new block, however by that moment the compact filter might have not yet been constructed, which implies that if a peer asks for a filter, bitcoin core would just not respond. From the peer perspective this is a misbehaviour (we advertised a block and don't provide filers for it), which results in a disconnect/ban.\r\n\r\nMore precisely, [BIP157](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0157.mediawiki#getcfilters) specifies:\r\n\r\n```\r\nStopHash MUST be known to belong to a block accepted by the receiving peer. This is the case if the peer had previously sent a headers or inv message with that block or any descendents. A node that receives getcfilters with an unknown StopHash SHOULD NOT respond.\r\n```\r\nCurrent behaviour clearly contradicts the above specification.\r\n\r\nI (re-)discovered it during a test a \"light\" compact block filter node [kyoto](https://github.com/2140-dev/kyoto) and [ldk-node](https://github.com/lightningdevkit/ldk-node).\r\n\r\n**Proposed solution:** compute filters on-the-fly if they are requested for blocks we already know. Filters do not commit to their predecessors on the contrary to the filter headers, thus we can independently compute them for a set of blocks, moreover we can compute them only once and store, thus sequential request would just go as usual by reading already computed filters. This does fix not hinder block processing and propagation.\r\n\r\nWith this change when a filter request is received it checks whether we have block data (if not abort), then checks if we have filter on disk, if not we calculate filter on-the-fly. Then we attempt to write the calculated filter, so the next request would be read instead of calculated (it is less computationally demanding, right?).\r\n\r\nTo write to the DB we need to have both filter and filter header, and the filter header commits to the previous header, which means we can only write if there is only a single block without filters (which is the case for normal operation when blocks are mined one by one).\r\n\r\nSome words about vulnerabilities: we expose the possibility that external peer can force our node to calculate filters on the fly and thus to load CPU. Given that the race condition can only occur when we already have processed blocks, but not yet constructed filters, this is a window on a scale of milliseconds, so it is fine.\r\n\r\nAlso it doesn't affect the initial block download, as during that time a node does not respond to compact filters messages.\r\n",
